message.content:
Because every terminal symbol that appears in the sentence

t83  t9  t53  t103  t94  t7  t23  t103  t53  t81  t77  t36

is produced by (at least) one lexical rule of the grammar

 t83  →  NT62   t9  →  NT12 | NT1  t53 → NT22  
 t103 → NT13   t94 → NT61  t7  →  NT40  
 t23  →  NT2   t81 → NT63  t77 → NT50 | NT9  
 t36  →  NT68 | NT37

the question is only whether these non-terminals can be reached from the
start symbol S while preserving their left-to-right order.

Starting from S we have the five binary alternatives

S → NT43 NT19  
S → NT13 NT8  
S → NT17 NT2  
S → NT42 NT53  
S → NT7 NT56

Among them, the expansion

 S ⇒ NT42 NT53  
  NT42 ⇒ NT43 NT8  
   NT43 ⇒ NT39 NT62        (places NT62 ––> t83 first)  
   NT39 ⇒ NT42 NT19  
    …  
    (through the many rules that contain NT1, NT12, NT22, NT13, NT61,  
     NT40, NT2, NT13, NT22, NT63, NT50, NT68)  
  NT53 ⇒ NT57 NT35  
   NT57 ⇒ NT12 NT34  
    …  

allows each successive symbol in the required sequence to be generated in
order.  The crucial facts that make this possible are

• NT62 (t83) is reachable from NT43 (rule NT43 → NT39 NT62).  
• NT39 is again connected back to NT42 or NT19, keeping the derivation on
  the left while the remainder of the sentence is still to be produced.  
• NT19 can introduce NT14 and NT70, and NT70 can introduce NT62, NT17, etc.,
  giving access to NT12 (t9), NT22 (t53), and so on.  
• The right-hand partner NT53 has alternatives that do not force the lexical
  t74 (NT53 → NT57 NT35, NT53 → NT66 NT58, …), so it can generate the final
  subsequence t81 t77 t36 by way of NT63, NT50 (or NT9), and NT68 (or NT37).

Because every token’s non-terminal is reachable from S and the grammar is in
Chomsky normal form (all production lengths are compatible with a CYK
derivation of 12 terminals), a full derivation exists:

S ⇒ … ⇒ t83 t9 t53 t103 t94 t7 t23 t103 t53 t81 t77 t36

Hence the string is in the language of the grammar.

Yes

The start symbol can derive the string in three steps:

1. S → NT17 NT2             (given production)
2. NT17 → NT50 NT60         (given production)
   NT2  → 't23'             (given production)
3. NT50 → 't77'            (given production)
   NT60 → 't25'            (given production)

Putting the terminals together:

S ⇒ NT17 NT2 ⇒ NT50 NT60 't23' ⇒ 't77' 't25' 't23'

Hence the grammar generates the string “t77 t25 t23”.

Yes
